               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-118-person1241">
                  ELIZA 
                  GERRISH
               <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1241" type="surname" value="GERRISH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1241" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1241" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of 
               <persName id="t18270913-118-person1242">
                  John 
                  Manley Gerrish
               <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1242" type="surname" value="Manley Gerrish"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1242" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1242" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 7th of August I had this handkerchief to wash for a gentleman; I missed it about two o'clock in the afternoon, from the end of a table in my room: I had seen it a few minutes before - the prisoner had brought some bread to my house that day; I went up stairs, and when I returned he stood with his back to the table.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-118-person1243">
                  JOHN 
                  MANLEY GERRISH
               <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1243" type="surname" value="MANLEY GERRISH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1243" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1243" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I went next morning with an officer to a house, and found the prisoner in bed with a young woman; I told him about the handkerchief; he asked if I had any children to take it away; I told him No, and he had better give it up, as my wife would lose the family washing: I then gave charge of him, and, as we went along, he said it was pawned, and he had thrown away the duplicate, but the officer found it on the witness.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-118-person1244">
                  EDMUND 
                  GROVER
               <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1244" type="surname" value="GROVER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1244" type="given" value="EDMUND"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1244" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the morning the prisoner of him; I taken, I bought the duplicate of a handkerchief of him; I sent my wife to the pawnbroker's, and she brought back this handkerchief; I put it on my neck; the officer and Mr. Gerrish came and claimed it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-118-person1245">
                  RICHARD 
                  CONSTANTINE
               <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1245" type="surname" value="CONSTANTINE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1245" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-118-person1245" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer, and apprehended the prisoner; he at first said he had not taken it; we then went to a public-house; some people there said to him, "Why don't you tell the truth? the poor woman will lose her washing:" he then took me to the pawnbroker, who said he was the man who pawned it; he then told me who he had sold the duplicate to.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18270913-118-verdict675" type="verdictDescription">
